</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Imaging of the gallbladder has a key role in the examination of patients with abdominal pain—especially pain localized to the right upper quadrant. Pathologic conditions that affect the gallbladder include cholelithiasis and associated complications such as acute and chronic cholecystitis, choledocholithiasis, gallstone pancreatitis, and cancer. Modalities used to image the gallbladder include ultrasonography (US), computed tomography (CT), magnetic resonance (MR) imaging, and nuclear scintigraphy. US is the primary imaging modality used to evaluate entities suspected of being gallbladder disease, as it is both sensitive and specific for demonstrating gallstones, biliary duct dilatation, and inflammatory features. However, CT is often the first imaging examination performed in patients who present to the emergency department with acute abdominal pain. Because the CT appearance of gallstones is variable, depending on the composition of the stone, pattern of calcification, and presence of gas, gallstones and other gallbladder conditions can be difficult to detect at conventional multidetector CT, with which data are acquired by using a single x-ray energy spectrum. Dual-energy CT, with which one takes advantage of the material-dependent x-ray absorption behavior of concurrently acquired high– and low–kilovolt-peak data, can add value by increasing the conspicuity of noncalcified gallstones and improving the detection of acute cholecystitis and gallbladder malignancy. In addition, MR cholangiopancreatography can be helpful for assessing choledocholithiasis and complicated biliary duct disease.</div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2018</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2018170076">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2018170076">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170076/asset/images/large/rg.2018170076.fig1a.jpeg" height="1034" width="1200" aria-labelledby="fig1a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span>. Creation of iodine-selective images with dual-energy CT postprocessing in a patient with perforated cholecystitis. <b>(a)</b> Coronal mixed dual-energy CT image created by combining low– and high–kilovolt-peak data to simulate a conventional single-energy image shows a perforated gallbladder, with discontinuity of the gallbladder wall (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Coronal virtual nonenhanced CT image created by artificially removing the calculated iodine content. <b>(c)</b> Coronal iodine overlay CT map shows the iodine content in color on top of the gray-scale virtual nonenhanced images.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170076&amp;id=fig1a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170076/asset/images/large/rg.2018170076.fig1b.jpeg" height="1142" width="1325" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span>. Creation of iodine-selective images with dual-energy CT postprocessing in a patient with perforated cholecystitis. <b>(a)</b> Coronal mixed dual-energy CT image created by combining low– and high–kilovolt-peak data to simulate a conventional single-energy image shows a perforated gallbladder, with discontinuity of the gallbladder wall (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Coronal virtual nonenhanced CT image created by artificially removing the calculated iodine content. <b>(c)</b> Coronal iodine overlay CT map shows the iodine content in color on top of the gray-scale virtual nonenhanced images.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170076&amp;id=fig1b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170076/asset/images/large/rg.2018170076.fig1c.jpeg" height="1142" width="1325" aria-labelledby="fig1c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1c</span>. Creation of iodine-selective images with dual-energy CT postprocessing in a patient with perforated cholecystitis. <b>(a)</b> Coronal mixed dual-energy CT image created by combining low– and high–kilovolt-peak data to simulate a conventional single-energy image shows a perforated gallbladder, with discontinuity of the gallbladder wall (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Coronal virtual nonenhanced CT image created by artificially removing the calculated iodine content. <b>(c)</b> Coronal iodine overlay CT map shows the iodine content in color on top of the gray-scale virtual nonenhanced images.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170076&amp;id=fig1c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170076/asset/images/large/rg.2018170076.fig2.jpeg" height="1088" width="1394" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span>. Normal biliary tree. Coronal maximum intensity projection MR cholangiopancreatography image shows the normal appearance of the gallbladder (straight arrow) and cystic duct (curved arrow) inserting into the extrahepatic duct, marking the division between the CBD and common hepatic duct (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170076&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170076/asset/images/large/rg.2018170076.fig3a.jpeg" height="1590" width="1325" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span>. Complications of cholelithiasis. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image in a 58-year-old man shows peripancreatic inflammatory changes (straight arrows) and fluid (curved arrow) due to acute pancreatitis caused by a punctate calcified gallstone at the ampulla (arrowhead), consistent with gallstone pancreatitis. <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT image enhanced with intravenous and oral contrast media in a 32-year-old woman shows a distended stomach and multiple dilated loops of small bowel, with oral contrast material (arrowhead) in a gallbladder-duodenal fistula and a 4.0-cm noncalcified gallstone (arrow) in the distal ileum, consistent with gallstone ileus. <b>(c)</b> Axial T2-weighted fat-saturated MR image in a 57-year-old man who presented with nausea, vomiting, malaise, and weight loss shows dilatation of the intrahepatic bile ducts (arrows). <b>(d)</b> Coronal MR cholangiopancreatographic image in the patient in <b>c</b> shows intrahepatic biliary duct dilatation (curved arrows), with obstruction just distal to the confluence of the hepatic ducts, secondary to external compression by two stones (straight arrows) in the cystic duct or gallbladder neck. Findings in <b>c</b> and <b>d</b> are consistent with Mirizzi syndrome.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170076&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170076/asset/images/large/rg.2018170076.fig3b.jpeg" height="1590" width="1325" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span>. Complications of cholelithiasis. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image in a 58-year-old man shows peripancreatic inflammatory changes (straight arrows) and fluid (curved arrow) due to acute pancreatitis caused by a punctate calcified gallstone at the ampulla (arrowhead), consistent with gallstone pancreatitis. <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT image enhanced with intravenous and oral contrast media in a 32-year-old woman shows a distended stomach and multiple dilated loops of small bowel, with oral contrast material (arrowhead) in a gallbladder-duodenal fistula and a 4.0-cm noncalcified gallstone (arrow) in the distal ileum, consistent with gallstone ileus. <b>(c)</b> Axial T2-weighted fat-saturated MR image in a 57-year-old man who presented with nausea, vomiting, malaise, and weight loss shows dilatation of the intrahepatic bile ducts (arrows). <b>(d)</b> Coronal MR cholangiopancreatographic image in the patient in <b>c</b> shows intrahepatic biliary duct dilatation (curved arrows), with obstruction just distal to the confluence of the hepatic ducts, secondary to external compression by two stones (straight arrows) in the cystic duct or gallbladder neck. Findings in <b>c</b> and <b>d</b> are consistent with Mirizzi syndrome.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170076&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170076/asset/images/large/rg.2018170076.fig3c.jpeg" height="1384" width="1266" aria-labelledby="fig3c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3c</span>. Complications of cholelithiasis. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image in a 58-year-old man shows peripancreatic inflammatory changes (straight arrows) and fluid (curved arrow) due to acute pancreatitis caused by a punctate calcified gallstone at the ampulla (arrowhead), consistent with gallstone pancreatitis. <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT image enhanced with intravenous and oral contrast media in a 32-year-old woman shows a distended stomach and multiple dilated loops of small bowel, with oral contrast material (arrowhead) in a gallbladder-duodenal fistula and a 4.0-cm noncalcified gallstone (arrow) in the distal ileum, consistent with gallstone ileus. <b>(c)</b> Axial T2-weighted fat-saturated MR image in a 57-year-old man who presented with nausea, vomiting, malaise, and weight loss shows dilatation of the intrahepatic bile ducts (arrows). <b>(d)</b> Coronal MR cholangiopancreatographic image in the patient in <b>c</b> shows intrahepatic biliary duct dilatation (curved arrows), with obstruction just distal to the confluence of the hepatic ducts, secondary to external compression by two stones (straight arrows) in the cystic duct or gallbladder neck. Findings in <b>c</b> and <b>d</b> are consistent with Mirizzi syndrome.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170076&amp;id=fig3c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170076/asset/images/large/rg.2018170076.fig3d.jpeg" height="1384" width="1384" aria-labelledby="fig3d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3d</span>. Complications of cholelithiasis. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image in a 58-year-old man shows peripancreatic inflammatory changes (straight arrows) and fluid (curved arrow) due to acute pancreatitis caused by a punctate calcified gallstone at the ampulla (arrowhead), consistent with gallstone pancreatitis. <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT image enhanced with intravenous and oral contrast media in a 32-year-old woman shows a distended stomach and multiple dilated loops of small bowel, with oral contrast material (arrowhead) in a gallbladder-duodenal fistula and a 4.0-cm noncalcified gallstone (arrow) in the distal ileum, consistent with gallstone ileus. <b>(c)</b> Axial T2-weighted fat-saturated MR image in a 57-year-old man who presented with nausea, vomiting, malaise, and weight loss shows dilatation of the intrahepatic bile ducts (arrows). <b>(d)</b> Coronal MR cholangiopancreatographic image in the patient in <b>c</b> shows intrahepatic biliary duct dilatation (curved arrows), with obstruction just distal to the confluence of the hepatic ducts, secondary to external compression by two stones (straight arrows) in the cystic duct or gallbladder neck. Findings in <b>c</b> and <b>d</b> are consistent with Mirizzi syndrome.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170076&amp;id=fig3d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170076/asset/images/large/rg.2018170076.fig4a.jpeg" height="1193" width="1325" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span>. Variable CT appearances of gallstones in four patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows peripherally calcified gallstones (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a noncalcified gallstone (arrow) in a dilated CBD (arrowhead). <b>(c)</b> Coronal CT image shows gallstones (arrow) with nitrogenous gas within the central fissures; this appearance is known as the “Mercedes-Benz” sign. <b>(d)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows noncalcified gallstones (arrows) containing nitrogenous gas.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170076&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170076/asset/images/large/rg.2018170076.fig4b.jpeg" height="1193" width="1325" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span>. Variable CT appearances of gallstones in four patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows peripherally calcified gallstones (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a noncalcified gallstone (arrow) in a dilated CBD (arrowhead). <b>(c)</b> Coronal CT image shows gallstones (arrow) with nitrogenous gas within the central fissures; this appearance is known as the “Mercedes-Benz” sign. <b>(d)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows noncalcified gallstones (arrows) containing nitrogenous gas.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170076&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170076/asset/images/large/rg.2018170076.fig4c.jpeg" height="1193" width="1326" aria-labelledby="fig4c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4c</span>. Variable CT appearances of gallstones in four patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows peripherally calcified gallstones (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a noncalcified gallstone (arrow) in a dilated CBD (arrowhead). <b>(c)</b> Coronal CT image shows gallstones (arrow) with nitrogenous gas within the central fissures; this appearance is known as the “Mercedes-Benz” sign. <b>(d)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows noncalcified gallstones (arrows) containing nitrogenous gas.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170076&amp;id=fig4c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170076/asset/images/large/rg.2018170076.fig4d.jpeg" height="1193" width="1326" aria-labelledby="fig4d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4d</span>. Variable CT appearances of gallstones in four patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows peripherally calcified gallstones (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a noncalcified gallstone (arrow) in a dilated CBD (arrowhead). <b>(c)</b> Coronal CT image shows gallstones (arrow) with nitrogenous gas within the central fissures; this appearance is known as the “Mercedes-Benz” sign. <b>(d)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows noncalcified gallstones (arrows) containing nitrogenous gas.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170076&amp;id=fig4d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170076/asset/images/large/rg.2018170076.fig5a.jpeg" height="1057" width="1325" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span>. <b>(a–c)</b> Axial dual-energy CT virtual monochromatic postprocessing performed to increase the conspicuity of noncalcified gallstones. <b>(a)</b> On a 70-keV image, no calcified stones in the gallbladder (arrow) are readily seen. <b>(b)</b> On a 40-keV image, gallstones (arrow) are hypoattenuating to surrounding bile and readily apparent. <b>(c)</b> On a 190-keV image, gallstones (arrow) appear hyperattenuating to surrounding bile. <b>(d)</b> Findings on transverse US image of the gallbladder confirm the presence of a 2.4-cm gallstone (calipers).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170076&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170076/asset/images/large/rg.2018170076.fig5b.jpeg" height="1057" width="1325" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span>. <b>(a–c)</b> Axial dual-energy CT virtual monochromatic postprocessing performed to increase the conspicuity of noncalcified gallstones. <b>(a)</b> On a 70-keV image, no calcified stones in the gallbladder (arrow) are readily seen. <b>(b)</b> On a 40-keV image, gallstones (arrow) are hypoattenuating to surrounding bile and readily apparent. <b>(c)</b> On a 190-keV image, gallstones (arrow) appear hyperattenuating to surrounding bile. <b>(d)</b> Findings on transverse US image of the gallbladder confirm the presence of a 2.4-cm gallstone (calipers).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170076&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170076/asset/images/large/rg.2018170076.fig5c.jpeg" height="1057" width="1325" aria-labelledby="fig5c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5c</span>. <b>(a–c)</b> Axial dual-energy CT virtual monochromatic postprocessing performed to increase the conspicuity of noncalcified gallstones. <b>(a)</b> On a 70-keV image, no calcified stones in the gallbladder (arrow) are readily seen. <b>(b)</b> On a 40-keV image, gallstones (arrow) are hypoattenuating to surrounding bile and readily apparent. <b>(c)</b> On a 190-keV image, gallstones (arrow) appear hyperattenuating to surrounding bile. <b>(d)</b> Findings on transverse US image of the gallbladder confirm the presence of a 2.4-cm gallstone (calipers).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170076&amp;id=fig5c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170076/asset/images/large/rg.2018170076.fig5d.jpeg" height="1057" width="1325" aria-labelledby="fig5d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5d</span>. <b>(a–c)</b> Axial dual-energy CT virtual monochromatic postprocessing performed to increase the conspicuity of noncalcified gallstones. <b>(a)</b> On a 70-keV image, no calcified stones in the gallbladder (arrow) are readily seen. <b>(b)</b> On a 40-keV image, gallstones (arrow) are hypoattenuating to surrounding bile and readily apparent. <b>(c)</b> On a 190-keV image, gallstones (arrow) appear hyperattenuating to surrounding bile. <b>(d)</b> Findings on transverse US image of the gallbladder confirm the presence of a 2.4-cm gallstone (calipers).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170076&amp;id=fig5d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170076/asset/images/large/rg.2018170076.fig6a.jpeg" height="1126" width="1357" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span>. Cholelithiasis at MR imaging. <b>(a)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image shows multiple hypointense stones (arrow) within the gallbladder. <b>(b)</b> Coronal MR cholangiopancreatographic image shows cholelithiasis (curved arrow), with a stone (straight arrow) in the gallbladder neck.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170076&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170076/asset/images/large/rg.2018170076.fig6b.jpeg" height="1126" width="891" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span>. Cholelithiasis at MR imaging. <b>(a)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image shows multiple hypointense stones (arrow) within the gallbladder. <b>(b)</b> Coronal MR cholangiopancreatographic image shows cholelithiasis (curved arrow), with a stone (straight arrow) in the gallbladder neck.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170076&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170076/asset/images/large/rg.2018170076.fig7a.jpeg" height="1151" width="1234" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. Noncalcified CBD stone. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a round hyperattenuating noncalcified mass (arrow) in a dilated distal CBD, with mild intrahepatic biliary duct dilatation. This lesion was thought to represent a stone or, less likely, a biliary mass. <b>(b, c)</b> Findings on axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image <b>(b)</b> and T2-weighted maximum intensity projection MR cholangiopancreatographic image <b>(c)</b> confirm the diagnosis of a large nonenhancing CBD stone (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170076&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170076/asset/images/large/rg.2018170076.fig7b.jpeg" height="1151" width="1233" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span>. Noncalcified CBD stone. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a round hyperattenuating noncalcified mass (arrow) in a dilated distal CBD, with mild intrahepatic biliary duct dilatation. This lesion was thought to represent a stone or, less likely, a biliary mass. <b>(b, c)</b> Findings on axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image <b>(b)</b> and T2-weighted maximum intensity projection MR cholangiopancreatographic image <b>(c)</b> confirm the diagnosis of a large nonenhancing CBD stone (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170076&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170076/asset/images/large/rg.2018170076.fig7c.jpeg" height="1151" width="1234" aria-labelledby="fig7c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7c</span>. Noncalcified CBD stone. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a round hyperattenuating noncalcified mass (arrow) in a dilated distal CBD, with mild intrahepatic biliary duct dilatation. This lesion was thought to represent a stone or, less likely, a biliary mass. <b>(b, c)</b> Findings on axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image <b>(b)</b> and T2-weighted maximum intensity projection MR cholangiopancreatographic image <b>(c)</b> confirm the diagnosis of a large nonenhancing CBD stone (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170076&amp;id=fig7c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170076/asset/images/large/rg.2018170076.fig8a.jpeg" height="1132" width="1360" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. Acute cholecystitis in three patients. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal US image shows gallbladder wall thickening (straight arrow), pericholecystic fluid (curved arrow), and multiple echogenic stones (arrowhead) with posterior acoustic shadowing. These findings are consistent with acute calculous cholecystitis, which was confirmed with pathologic analysis after subsequently performed laparoscopic cholecystectomy. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image in another patient shows pericholecystic fluid and fat stranding (arrow), and a small calcified stone (arrowhead) in the CBD. <b>(c)</b> Findings on subsequently obtained endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatographic image in the patient in <b>b</b> confirm the presence of acute cholecystitis with choledocholithiasis, without visualization of the cystic duct and gallbladder, and multiple filling defects (arrow) in the CBD. <b>(d)</b> Coronal dual-energy CT iodine overlay image in a different patient with acute cholecystitis shows increased iodine uptake (arrowhead) in the pericholecystic hepatic parenchyma, known as the “dual-energy CT hot rim” sign, and increased uptake in the gallbladder wall (arrow), known as the “dual-energy CT hot gallbladder” sign.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170076&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170076/asset/images/large/rg.2018170076.fig8b.jpeg" height="1132" width="1292" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. Acute cholecystitis in three patients. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal US image shows gallbladder wall thickening (straight arrow), pericholecystic fluid (curved arrow), and multiple echogenic stones (arrowhead) with posterior acoustic shadowing. These findings are consistent with acute calculous cholecystitis, which was confirmed with pathologic analysis after subsequently performed laparoscopic cholecystectomy. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image in another patient shows pericholecystic fluid and fat stranding (arrow), and a small calcified stone (arrowhead) in the CBD. <b>(c)</b> Findings on subsequently obtained endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatographic image in the patient in <b>b</b> confirm the presence of acute cholecystitis with choledocholithiasis, without visualization of the cystic duct and gallbladder, and multiple filling defects (arrow) in the CBD. <b>(d)</b> Coronal dual-energy CT iodine overlay image in a different patient with acute cholecystitis shows increased iodine uptake (arrowhead) in the pericholecystic hepatic parenchyma, known as the “dual-energy CT hot rim” sign, and increased uptake in the gallbladder wall (arrow), known as the “dual-energy CT hot gallbladder” sign.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170076&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170076/asset/images/large/rg.2018170076.fig8c.jpeg" height="1164" width="1324" aria-labelledby="fig8c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8c</span>. Acute cholecystitis in three patients. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal US image shows gallbladder wall thickening (straight arrow), pericholecystic fluid (curved arrow), and multiple echogenic stones (arrowhead) with posterior acoustic shadowing. These findings are consistent with acute calculous cholecystitis, which was confirmed with pathologic analysis after subsequently performed laparoscopic cholecystectomy. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image in another patient shows pericholecystic fluid and fat stranding (arrow), and a small calcified stone (arrowhead) in the CBD. <b>(c)</b> Findings on subsequently obtained endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatographic image in the patient in <b>b</b> confirm the presence of acute cholecystitis with choledocholithiasis, without visualization of the cystic duct and gallbladder, and multiple filling defects (arrow) in the CBD. <b>(d)</b> Coronal dual-energy CT iodine overlay image in a different patient with acute cholecystitis shows increased iodine uptake (arrowhead) in the pericholecystic hepatic parenchyma, known as the “dual-energy CT hot rim” sign, and increased uptake in the gallbladder wall (arrow), known as the “dual-energy CT hot gallbladder” sign.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170076&amp;id=fig8c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170076/asset/images/large/rg.2018170076.fig8d.jpeg" height="1163" width="1328" aria-labelledby="fig8d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8d</span>. Acute cholecystitis in three patients. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal US image shows gallbladder wall thickening (straight arrow), pericholecystic fluid (curved arrow), and multiple echogenic stones (arrowhead) with posterior acoustic shadowing. These findings are consistent with acute calculous cholecystitis, which was confirmed with pathologic analysis after subsequently performed laparoscopic cholecystectomy. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image in another patient shows pericholecystic fluid and fat stranding (arrow), and a small calcified stone (arrowhead) in the CBD. <b>(c)</b> Findings on subsequently obtained endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatographic image in the patient in <b>b</b> confirm the presence of acute cholecystitis with choledocholithiasis, without visualization of the cystic duct and gallbladder, and multiple filling defects (arrow) in the CBD. <b>(d)</b> Coronal dual-energy CT iodine overlay image in a different patient with acute cholecystitis shows increased iodine uptake (arrowhead) in the pericholecystic hepatic parenchyma, known as the “dual-energy CT hot rim” sign, and increased uptake in the gallbladder wall (arrow), known as the “dual-energy CT hot gallbladder” sign.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170076&amp;id=fig8d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170076/asset/images/large/rg.2018170076.fig9a.jpeg" height="1170" width="1354" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. Troubleshooting indeterminate CT findings of acute cholecystitis at MR cholangiopancreatography. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows nonspecific gallbladder wall thickening (arrow) but no calcified gallstones. <b>(b)</b> Coronal MR cholangiopancreatographic image subsequently obtained on the same day as the CT image shows pericholecystic fluid (straight arrow), multiple gallstones (arrowhead), and a large calculus (curved arrow) in the gallbladder neck.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170076&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170076/asset/images/large/rg.2018170076.fig9b.jpeg" height="1170" width="995" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span>. Troubleshooting indeterminate CT findings of acute cholecystitis at MR cholangiopancreatography. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows nonspecific gallbladder wall thickening (arrow) but no calcified gallstones. <b>(b)</b> Coronal MR cholangiopancreatographic image subsequently obtained on the same day as the CT image shows pericholecystic fluid (straight arrow), multiple gallstones (arrowhead), and a large calculus (curved arrow) in the gallbladder neck.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170076&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170076/asset/images/large/rg.2018170076.fig10a.jpeg" height="1301" width="1436" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span>. HIDA scans of acute cholecystitis. <b>(a)</b> Anterior scan obtained 5 minutes after administration of the tracer shows normal homogeneous tracer activity within the liver. <b>(b)</b> Anterior scan obtained at 15 minutes shows normal tracer activity in the CBD (straight arrow) and duodenum (curved arrow). <b>(c)</b> Anterior scan obtained at 60 minutes shows no tracer activity in the expected location in the gallbladder fossa (straight arrow) despite visualization of the CBD and small bowel (curved arrows). <b>(d)</b> On an anterior scan obtained at 30 minutes after the intravenous administration of morphine, there is persistent nonvisualization of the gallbladder (straight arrow), with tracer activity seen in the small bowel and stomach (curved arrows). These findings are diagnostic of acute cholecystitis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170076&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170076/asset/images/large/rg.2018170076.fig10b.jpeg" height="1235" width="1232" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span>. HIDA scans of acute cholecystitis. <b>(a)</b> Anterior scan obtained 5 minutes after administration of the tracer shows normal homogeneous tracer activity within the liver. <b>(b)</b> Anterior scan obtained at 15 minutes shows normal tracer activity in the CBD (straight arrow) and duodenum (curved arrow). <b>(c)</b> Anterior scan obtained at 60 minutes shows no tracer activity in the expected location in the gallbladder fossa (straight arrow) despite visualization of the CBD and small bowel (curved arrows). <b>(d)</b> On an anterior scan obtained at 30 minutes after the intravenous administration of morphine, there is persistent nonvisualization of the gallbladder (straight arrow), with tracer activity seen in the small bowel and stomach (curved arrows). These findings are diagnostic of acute cholecystitis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170076&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170076/asset/images/large/rg.2018170076.fig10c.jpeg" height="1234" width="1235" aria-labelledby="fig10c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10c</span>. HIDA scans of acute cholecystitis. <b>(a)</b> Anterior scan obtained 5 minutes after administration of the tracer shows normal homogeneous tracer activity within the liver. <b>(b)</b> Anterior scan obtained at 15 minutes shows normal tracer activity in the CBD (straight arrow) and duodenum (curved arrow). <b>(c)</b> Anterior scan obtained at 60 minutes shows no tracer activity in the expected location in the gallbladder fossa (straight arrow) despite visualization of the CBD and small bowel (curved arrows). <b>(d)</b> On an anterior scan obtained at 30 minutes after the intravenous administration of morphine, there is persistent nonvisualization of the gallbladder (straight arrow), with tracer activity seen in the small bowel and stomach (curved arrows). These findings are diagnostic of acute cholecystitis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170076&amp;id=fig10c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170076/asset/images/large/rg.2018170076.fig10d.jpeg" height="1234" width="1235" aria-labelledby="fig10d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10d</span>. HIDA scans of acute cholecystitis. <b>(a)</b> Anterior scan obtained 5 minutes after administration of the tracer shows normal homogeneous tracer activity within the liver. <b>(b)</b> Anterior scan obtained at 15 minutes shows normal tracer activity in the CBD (straight arrow) and duodenum (curved arrow). <b>(c)</b> Anterior scan obtained at 60 minutes shows no tracer activity in the expected location in the gallbladder fossa (straight arrow) despite visualization of the CBD and small bowel (curved arrows). <b>(d)</b> On an anterior scan obtained at 30 minutes after the intravenous administration of morphine, there is persistent nonvisualization of the gallbladder (straight arrow), with tracer activity seen in the small bowel and stomach (curved arrows). These findings are diagnostic of acute cholecystitis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170076&amp;id=fig10d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170076/asset/images/large/rg.2018170076.fig11a.jpeg" height="1238" width="1183" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span>. Complications of acute cholecystitis. <b>(a)</b> US image shows a gallbladder containing weblike internal echoes (straight arrow), which represent sloughed membranes and debris; a thickened wall; and pericholecystic fluid (curved arrow)—findings consistent with gangrenous cholecystitis. <b>(b)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image shows a discontinuous posterior gallbladder wall (arrows), with extraluminal gallstones (arrowhead)—findings consistent with perforated cholecystitis. <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows gas (arrows) within the gallbladder, wall thickening, and pericholecystic fluid (arrowhead), consistent with emphysematous cholecystitis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170076&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170076/asset/images/large/rg.2018170076.fig11b.jpeg" height="1238" width="1335" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span>. Complications of acute cholecystitis. <b>(a)</b> US image shows a gallbladder containing weblike internal echoes (straight arrow), which represent sloughed membranes and debris; a thickened wall; and pericholecystic fluid (curved arrow)—findings consistent with gangrenous cholecystitis. <b>(b)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image shows a discontinuous posterior gallbladder wall (arrows), with extraluminal gallstones (arrowhead)—findings consistent with perforated cholecystitis. <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows gas (arrows) within the gallbladder, wall thickening, and pericholecystic fluid (arrowhead), consistent with emphysematous cholecystitis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170076&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170076/asset/images/large/rg.2018170076.fig11c.jpeg" height="1237" width="1182" aria-labelledby="fig11c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11c</span>. Complications of acute cholecystitis. <b>(a)</b> US image shows a gallbladder containing weblike internal echoes (straight arrow), which represent sloughed membranes and debris; a thickened wall; and pericholecystic fluid (curved arrow)—findings consistent with gangrenous cholecystitis. <b>(b)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image shows a discontinuous posterior gallbladder wall (arrows), with extraluminal gallstones (arrowhead)—findings consistent with perforated cholecystitis. <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows gas (arrows) within the gallbladder, wall thickening, and pericholecystic fluid (arrowhead), consistent with emphysematous cholecystitis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170076&amp;id=fig11c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170076/asset/images/large/rg.2018170076.fig12.jpeg" height="1449" width="1200" aria-labelledby="fig12" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12</span>. Xanthogranulomatous cholecystitis. Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows multiple hypoattenuating intramural nodules (arrows), or xantho-granulomas.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170076&amp;id=fig12">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170076/asset/images/large/rg.2018170076.fig13a.jpeg" height="1009" width="1007" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span>. Dual-energy CT differentiation between adenomyomatosis and gallbladder carcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Axial iodine overlay dual-energy CT image shows no iodine content within a masslike lesion (arrow) at the gallbladder fundus, supporting the suspicion of adenomyomatosis. <b>(b)</b> Axial mixed dual-energy CT image in a different patient shows a soft-tissue mass (arrow) extending from the gallbladder into the liver. <b>(c)</b> Axial iodine overlay dual-energy CT image in the patient in <b>b</b> shows increased iodine uptake (arrow) within the mass, which is of concern for carcinoma. <b>(d, e)</b> Fluorine 18 fluorodeoxyglucose (FDG) positron emission tomography (PET)/CT images in the same patient show an FDG-avid gallbladder mass (arrowhead in <b>d</b>) with extensive lymphadenopathy (arrows in <b>e</b>). Biopsy results confirmed the diagnosis of metastatic gallbladder carcinoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170076&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170076/asset/images/large/rg.2018170076.fig13b.jpeg" height="1009" width="1346" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span>. Dual-energy CT differentiation between adenomyomatosis and gallbladder carcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Axial iodine overlay dual-energy CT image shows no iodine content within a masslike lesion (arrow) at the gallbladder fundus, supporting the suspicion of adenomyomatosis. <b>(b)</b> Axial mixed dual-energy CT image in a different patient shows a soft-tissue mass (arrow) extending from the gallbladder into the liver. <b>(c)</b> Axial iodine overlay dual-energy CT image in the patient in <b>b</b> shows increased iodine uptake (arrow) within the mass, which is of concern for carcinoma. <b>(d, e)</b> Fluorine 18 fluorodeoxyglucose (FDG) positron emission tomography (PET)/CT images in the same patient show an FDG-avid gallbladder mass (arrowhead in <b>d</b>) with extensive lymphadenopathy (arrows in <b>e</b>). Biopsy results confirmed the diagnosis of metastatic gallbladder carcinoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170076&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170076/asset/images/large/rg.2018170076.fig13c.jpeg" height="1009" width="1345" aria-labelledby="fig13c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13c</span>. Dual-energy CT differentiation between adenomyomatosis and gallbladder carcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Axial iodine overlay dual-energy CT image shows no iodine content within a masslike lesion (arrow) at the gallbladder fundus, supporting the suspicion of adenomyomatosis. <b>(b)</b> Axial mixed dual-energy CT image in a different patient shows a soft-tissue mass (arrow) extending from the gallbladder into the liver. <b>(c)</b> Axial iodine overlay dual-energy CT image in the patient in <b>b</b> shows increased iodine uptake (arrow) within the mass, which is of concern for carcinoma. <b>(d, e)</b> Fluorine 18 fluorodeoxyglucose (FDG) positron emission tomography (PET)/CT images in the same patient show an FDG-avid gallbladder mass (arrowhead in <b>d</b>) with extensive lymphadenopathy (arrows in <b>e</b>). Biopsy results confirmed the diagnosis of metastatic gallbladder carcinoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170076&amp;id=fig13c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170076/asset/images/large/rg.2018170076.fig13d.jpeg" height="1379" width="1225" aria-labelledby="fig13d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13d</span>. Dual-energy CT differentiation between adenomyomatosis and gallbladder carcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Axial iodine overlay dual-energy CT image shows no iodine content within a masslike lesion (arrow) at the gallbladder fundus, supporting the suspicion of adenomyomatosis. <b>(b)</b> Axial mixed dual-energy CT image in a different patient shows a soft-tissue mass (arrow) extending from the gallbladder into the liver. <b>(c)</b> Axial iodine overlay dual-energy CT image in the patient in <b>b</b> shows increased iodine uptake (arrow) within the mass, which is of concern for carcinoma. <b>(d, e)</b> Fluorine 18 fluorodeoxyglucose (FDG) positron emission tomography (PET)/CT images in the same patient show an FDG-avid gallbladder mass (arrowhead in <b>d</b>) with extensive lymphadenopathy (arrows in <b>e</b>). Biopsy results confirmed the diagnosis of metastatic gallbladder carcinoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170076&amp;id=fig13d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170076/asset/images/large/rg.2018170076.fig13e.jpeg" height="1379" width="1225" aria-labelledby="fig13e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13e</span>. Dual-energy CT differentiation between adenomyomatosis and gallbladder carcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Axial iodine overlay dual-energy CT image shows no iodine content within a masslike lesion (arrow) at the gallbladder fundus, supporting the suspicion of adenomyomatosis. <b>(b)</b> Axial mixed dual-energy CT image in a different patient shows a soft-tissue mass (arrow) extending from the gallbladder into the liver. <b>(c)</b> Axial iodine overlay dual-energy CT image in the patient in <b>b</b> shows increased iodine uptake (arrow) within the mass, which is of concern for carcinoma. <b>(d, e)</b> Fluorine 18 fluorodeoxyglucose (FDG) positron emission tomography (PET)/CT images in the same patient show an FDG-avid gallbladder mass (arrowhead in <b>d</b>) with extensive lymphadenopathy (arrows in <b>e</b>). Biopsy results confirmed the diagnosis of metastatic gallbladder carcinoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170076&amp;id=fig13e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170076/asset/images/large/rg.2018170076.fig14.jpeg" height="1243" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig14" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14</span>. Adenomyomatosis. Axial T2-weighted MR image shows multiple hyperintense foci in a curvilinear arrangement (circle), producing the pearl necklace sign that is characteristic of adenomyomatosis, in the gallbladder wall.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170076&amp;id=fig14">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170076/asset/images/large/rg.2018170076.fig15a.jpeg" height="1514" width="1275" aria-labelledby="fig15a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span>. Imaging patterns of gallbladder carcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows irregular diffuse gallbladder wall thickening (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows an intraluminal polypoid mass (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170076&amp;id=fig15a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170076/asset/images/large/rg.2018170076.fig15b.jpeg" height="1515" width="1365" aria-labelledby="fig15b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span>. Imaging patterns of gallbladder carcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows irregular diffuse gallbladder wall thickening (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows an intraluminal polypoid mass (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170076&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Russo MW, Wei JT, Thiny MT, et al. Digestive and liver diseases statistics, 2004. <em>Gastroenterology</em> 2004;126(5):1448–1453.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1053/j.gastro.2004.01.025"